### **Learning Track 2: Biomarker discovery**
Author (@slack): Mary Dhevanayagam (@Shanu)

Biomarkers are measurable characteristics such as genes, proteins, etc. that indicate a normal or abnormal process in the body. Biomarker discovery is the process of identifying, measuring and validating biomarkers in biological samples. Some applications of biomarkers include disease diagnosis, prognosis and monitoring treatment<sup>1,2</sup>.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

***Figure 1.*** The use of omics pipelines in biomarker discovery<sup>2</sup>.

The theory of central dogma of molecular biology states that the genetic information flows from the DNA to RNA to protein<sup>3</sup>. Transcriptomics is the study of the RNA transcripts<sup>4</sup>. Single-cell RNA-seq technology is used for cancer research to analyse tumour heterogeneity, gene expression patterns and signalling pathways<sup>5</sup>. 

AlphaFold is an AI system used for predicting protein structures with high accuracy<sup>6</sup>. AlphaFold was used to develop a novel CDK20 small molecule inhibitor for treatment of hepatocellular carcinoma in a cost- and time-efficient manner<sup>7</sup>. TCGA is a project that aimed to profile and analyse many types of human tumours to discover the molecular alterations<sup>8</sup>. COSMIC is a comprehensive database of somatic mutations causing human cancer <sup>9</sup>.

*TP53* gene mutations result in loss of tumour suppression activity of p53 protein, which is primarily involved in cell cycle arrest, DNA repair and apoptosis. *TP53* mutations can contribute to development of ovarian cancer, breast cancer and lung cancer<sup>10</sup>. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

***Figure 2.*** Effects of wild type p53 and mutated p53<sup>11</sup>.

*BRCA1* and *BRCA2* are tumour suppressor genes which if mutated can lead to malignancies such as breast cancer and ovarian cancer. *BRCA* gene mutations may result in accumulation of double-strand DNA breaks and lead to tumour development<sup>12</sup>. 

For breast cancer, over 2 million new cases reported in 2020 and more than 600,000 deaths in 2022<sup>13</sup>. Ovarian cancer had almost 300,000 new cases and over 180,000 deaths globally in 2018<sup>14</sup>. 

Immune checkpoint proteins are targeted to develop monoclonal antibodies for cancer immunotherapy. Biomarkers such as PDL-1 expression, hypoxia, etc. can help to predict patient response to immune checkpoint inhibitors<sup>15,16</sup>. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

***Figure 3.*** Immune checkpoints on different immune cells<sup>17</sup>.

Differential gene expression (DGE) occurs due to genetic or epigenetic changes in the genome, and DGE analysis is often used for RNA-seq data analysis. Upregulation is when there is increased activity or expression, while downregulation is when there is decreased activity or expression<sup>18</sup>. 

GPCRs are transmembrane proteins that may progress cancer development due to mutation, abnormal expression or hyperactivation<sup>19</sup>. Protein kinases are enzymes that facilitate cell proliferation and survival. Hence, overexpressed kinases are associated with cancer progression and recurrence<sup>20</sup>. Growth factors can regulate cancer progression by facilitating clonal expansion, invasion and angiogenesis of tumour cells. Hence, these growth factors can be targeted by cancer drugs<sup>21</sup>.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

***Figure 4.*** Cancer progression and growth factors<sup>21</sup>.
